      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, scale differences still matter for algorithms like k-nearest neighbors (k-NN) and others that rely on distance metrics. In k-NN, the distance between points is calculated using a norm (like Euclidean distance), so features with larger scales will dominate the distance calculation, effectively ignoring the smaller-scale features. While k-NN doesn't use gradient descent, it still depends on the relative magnitude of features to determine similarity. Normalizing or standardizing the features ensures that the distance metric treats all features equally, which is essential for accurate clustering or classification.",
      "source": "target",
